	Abstract = {The mate preferences of male Darwin's finches (Geospiza) were compared in areas of sympatry and allopatry, using female models in choice tests. Males from sympatric populations showed significantly stronger sexual preferences for conspecific females than did allopatric males. At one sympatric site (Isla Pinta), we found enhanced preferences for conspecific females despite the absence of character displacement in cues important for visual recognition. Lack of preferential male courtship is correlated with hybridization with immigrants in one allopatric population, Daphne Major G. fortis. Tests at other allopatric sites showed that the ability to distinguish unfamiliar species from conspecifics by visual cues varies among populations, and generally is better-developed on islands having more congeners.},
